  <a href="#1" id="1">
   An experiment with more than 1700 high blood pressure patients showed
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   that a blood and urine test can pinpoint those patients most likely to have a heart attack.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   The tests, which measure the activity of a blood protein called renin,
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   may also suggest a new risk factor for heart attacks.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   The study was conducted on people found to have mild to moderately high blood pressure.
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   Only 12% of these people had high renin "profiles".
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   But 7 heart attacks in this small group constituted the highest incidents of heart attacks.
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   The study has implications for drug makers as well as patients.
  </a>
